<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-463-254  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 463 254.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  April 1990 v22 n4 p14(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How small shareholders rebel. (Perspectives - EDP and the law)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Merisch, Dan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In Canadian law, derivative action is a form of legal proceedingwhere a minority shareholder in a corporation exercises rights inthe name of the corporation, rights which are usually theexclusive domain of management.andP;  Derivative action is important inthe computing industry because of its high level ofentrepreneurship which starts companies in which a minorityshareholder may be at risk.andP;  If a minority shareholder thinks thecompany is not being managed properly, the shareholder may ask thecourt for authorization to start a derivative action in the nameof the corporation against a third party.andP;  Before grantingauthorization, the court must be satisfied that company directorswill not bring or diligently prosecute the action, the shareholderasking for the authorization is acting in good faith, and theaction appears to be in the best interest of the corporation.andP;  Forthe court to be satisfied that the corporation's directors are notworking in the best interest of the corporation, there must be thesmell of improper self interest.andP;  Incompetence or high-risk takingare not sufficient grounds for the court to grant derivativeaction.andP;  The courts do not try to second-guess management in theordinary running of the corporation, even if it badly run, as longas it is honestly done.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Legal IssuesComputer IndustryManagementAccountabilityCanada.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>